english:
  title: Epitaph for Grand Lord Hong of Tangseong, Minister of Excellent Virtue
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: "The Nanyang Hongs are a renowned family of Samhan, generation after generation holding high office, yet their influence never crossed their borders. Among those who rose to prominence in the Middle Kingdom, some even became rebels. But Hong Kanggyeong alone served both the Central Court with unblemished honor and our nation as Chief Minister, his merits inscribed upon the state itself.\n\nThe Lord's name was Bin, his courtesy name Munnya. His ancestors had settled in Yanjing, and he was born in the Wuzi year of the Zhiyuan era. His parents cherished him deeply. Coming of age, he entered service in the inner court, gradually accumulating merit. In the Renzi year of the Huangqing era, through a superior's recommendation, he was appointed Assistant Commissioner of Bzhou under the Great Capital route. After serving with distinction, he was transferred to oversee the Paper Mill, advancing to the rank of Court Gentleman. His talent for administration earned universal respect.\n\nIn the Jisi year of the Tianli era, he became Judge of Songjiang Prefecture. Local officials dared not deceive him. When recalled to serve as Clerk of the Water Authority, he advanced again, never bending to pressure. Rising further to the Imperial Ritual Bureau, he briefly served until his father's passing.\n\nWhen Loyal and Straightforward King was slandered and detained in the capital for five years, this Lord labored tirelessly in his behalf, clarifying the king's innocence. Upon the king's restoration and return home in the Dingchou year of the Later Zhiyuan era, the king, remembering his loyal service, sought to retain him as political adviser. When the king requested an official position for him, he received appointment to the Pacification Office, but the king said, \"Litigation is beneath such a man. Why not entrust him with affairs of state?\" Thus he rose to Vice Director of Imperial Deliberation, holding the rank of Grand Commandant.\n\nIn the third lunar month of the Jimao year, following the late king's dying words, he assumed Acting Provincial Director. By autumn, Minister Cao Di secretly conspired with the Prince of Shen to depose the Loyal and Benevolent King, using the pretext of purging treacherous courtiers. They surrounded the Eternal Peace Palace where the late king's princess resided. Though Di had coerced the hundred officials, only this Lord stood firm. When Di attempted every stratagem to win him over, the Lord declared: \"This would be far greater error! Though the elder brother acts without restraint, the younger remains. What concern is this of Shen's prince?\" His refusal only hardened.\n\nWhen Di threatened to submit accusations against the king, this Lord stood immovable, preventing the envoy from proceeding. The Loyal and Benevolent King, skilled in riding and archery, burst through with elite warriors, crying out: \"The traitor is Di alone! Others acted only under duress. I know this well—fear nothing!\" After executing Di, he proclaimed: \"The old villain meets his deserved end. All others may rest assured.\" Though surrounded, the king recognized this Lord's steadfast righteousness and his crucial role in thwarting Di's conspiracy, and held him in profound gratitude.\n\nWhen the king traveled to the capital for interrogation by five imperial offices, he could not defend himself adequately. The situation grew perilous. Then this Lord spoke: \"Di was the king's servant. A servant who sought to harm his master faces the King's law without mercy. With weapons already engaged, who would seek to spare Di even a moment? Thus the king's culpability should be entirely remitted. I, being appointed Acting Director by the late king's will, bear full responsibility for matters of state governance. The king bears no guilt.\" His words carried such fervor that those who knew him trembled for his safety. Yet he said: \"If I do not vindicate my king's son, how can I face the late king below?\" \n\nWhen the king's honors were restored and he returned home, he bestowed upon this Lord the first rank of merit, elevated him to Grand Commandant, enfeoffed him as Lord of Tangseong with authority to establish a household, and declared: \"All matters of serving the Son of Heaven are managed by the Provincial Administration. If the left and right bureaus prove incompetent and affairs grow lax or improper, blame comes too late.\" He was then recommended to serve as Bureau Chief, advancing to Court Counselor.\n\nAfter the Mingzong succession, a man named Xu Zheng from the Central Plains falsely accused this Lord of disrespecting the throne, with Minister Cai providing false testimony. The investigation by the Central Secretariat revealed contradictions in their statements, and both were punished instead. The Lord said, \"I cannot remain here long,\" and proceeded to the capital. Those who knew him rejoiced: \"Munnya comes!\" They recommended him for high promotion, but he again sought appointment to the provinces, becoming Administrator of Xing'guo route with the rank of Eminent Counselor.\n\nIn governing the people, he employed benevolence; in controlling officials, he employed law. The people's gratitude endures to this day. In the Xinmao year, when Xuanzong ascended the throne and recorded the merits of loyal servants, he declared: \"Hong Bin has remained profoundly loyal from beginning to end, and among current surviving ministers of the late king, none equals him. He should assume the post of Prime Minister to assist in my governance.\" Thus was bestowed upon him the honorific \"Promoter of Sincerity, Supporter of the Dynasty, Concord with Virtue, Harmonious Intent, Aiding and Governing\"—ten characters of highest distinction. He was appointed to the rank of Trilateral Grand Commandant, Chief of the Board of Rites, and enfeoffed as Duke of Tangseong with Princely Household—the ancient honor granted to Prime Ministers, the greatest distinction for a minister.\n\nIn the twelfth lunar month of the Guisi year of the Zhizheng era, on the seventeenth day, he passed from illness at his residence, aged sixty-six. News of his passing reached the throne; the ruler grieved deeply, granted substantial memorial gifts, and bestowed the posthumous name \"Kanggyeong.\"\n\nHis line flourished: great-grandfather Chong was posthumously appointed Silver-Robed Grand Master; grandfather Se received high posthumous honors; father Yunshim was enfeoffed Lord of Nanyang. He married the Lady Gao, daughter of Minister of Rites Ko Insin. He fathered one son, Shoushan, who rose through Yuan service to various positions, attaining the rank of Court Gentleman. His grandson Gui now serves as Captain of the Guard. His granddaughter married Captain White Xuanji. His great-grandson Kang is yet young, as are White's daughters.\n\nWhen the Lord taught the Prefect, the renowned Master Hu Zhongyuan of Zhedong lodged at his house. My late father, Minister Gajing, served as Adjutant to the Provincial Government, becoming the Lord's colleague and close friend, thus allowing me to study under both. As evening approached and I prepared to leave, the Lord would always detain me, sometimes for more than a month. His hospitality and kindness ran deep.\n\nAlas, how can I decline to compose this epitaph? His virtue and governance are recorded in the national histories and preserved in stone archives, yet few have glimpsed them. To commit these to family chronicles and spread them through poetry is my duty, especially when the Prefect himself requests it.\n\nIn managing his household he was strict; in facing events he was decisive; in times of trouble he held to his principles unmovable—no ancient hero surpassed him. Truly, this Lord embodied clarity and fortitude supreme.\n\nAfter the Lord grew old, chaos descended upon the realm. His heart may thus be known. That stalwart and resolute spirit—shall it remain buried in the nine springs below, or shall it, like phoenix and unicorn, await the great peace and emerge anew? This I cannot know.\n\nThe epitaph reads:\n\nAh, Lord Hong,\nYou kept vigil in the palace,\nGrowing in years, raised to office,\nYour talent shone among the multitude.\nBy Yangtze's southern shore,\nTwice serving our realm,\nWherever you held post, duty was fulfilled,\nAnd people cherished your virtue.\n\nIn that age of lesser men,\nTroubling the throne,\nYour hatred burned\nLike charcoal against ice.\nWhen traitors found their opening,\nBringing calamity to the reign,\nYour voice alone spoke true,\nYour hand alone upheld right.\n\nThe late king declared:\n\"In my youth I knew your loyalty,\nAnd kept you ever in remembrance.\"\nThus he raised you to Prime Minister,\nGreatest among the hundred officials,\nHonoring virtue above all.\n\nAh, Lord Hong,\nRanks and stipends were abundant,\nYet descendants grew few—\nWho will succor their need?\nWho will succor their need?\n\nAh, Lord Hong."
  footnotes:
    - Samhan refers to the ancient kingdoms of Korea (Koguryo, Baekje, and Silla), used here to denote Korea generally.
    - The Zhiyuan era (至元) refers to the reign period of Kublai Khan, the Mongol Yuan emperor.
    - Yanjing is the ancient name for Beijing, the Yuan capital.
    - The 'late king' references refer to Loyal and Straightforward King (忠肅王), Hong Bin's patron.
    - The epitaph's final section is written in parallel prose style (parallelism), characteristic of traditional Chinese epitaphs.
